// Real content for each test-prep exam's "About [Exam]" Unit 1 (the
// placeholder unit built into renderAboutUnit() in maths-testprep-exam.html,
// modeled on Khan Academy's "About the SAT" pattern). Researched and written
// 2026-07-10 across 3 parallel research passes, each verified against the
// exam's own administering organization/state education department site or
// another reputable source, not written from memory. Keyed by the SAME
// lowercase exam slug used as testPrepData's top-level key in
// testprep-data.js (not the uppercase PROGRAM_ORDER codes from
// generate_testprep_data.py) — e.g. 'amc-8' with a hyphen, not 'AMC8'.
//
// Known open flags, worth a final check before this goes live:
// - SBA member-state list changes over time; deliberately not stated as a fixed list.
// - NJSLA's exact session length/item-type mix under its new 2026 adaptive format
//   wasn't fully confirmed in public sources yet; phrased with "typically" hedging.
// - CogAT retake policy is genuinely district-dependent, no single national rule.
// - MOEMS/AMC8/SSAT exact current registration fees weren't stated with confidence
//   (sources disagreed or figures shift year to year), described only in general
//   terms, pointing to the official site for current pricing. Re-check before publishing
//   if exact fee numbers are wanted on the page.
const testprepAboutContent = {
  moems: {
    whatIs: `The Math Olympiads for Elementary and Middle Schools (MOEMS) is a math competition for students in grades 3 through 8, run by the nonprofit organization Math Olympiads for Elementary and Middle Schools, Inc. Unlike a school placement test, MOEMS exists purely for recognition and enrichment: it gives students a chance to tackle creative, non-routine math problems that go beyond regular classroom work, and to see how they stack up against peers nationally and internationally. Students take part as members of a school or homeschool-association team (individuals cannot register on their own), guided by a teacher or parent coordinator known as a "PICO" (Person In Charge of Olympiads). MOEMS runs two divisions: Division E for grades 3 to 6, and Division M for grades 6 to 8 (any team with a 7th or 8th grader must compete in Division M). It's a low-stakes, high-engagement way to build problem-solving confidence and, for many kids, a first real taste of math competitions.`,
    formatScoring: `MOEMS is structured as five separate monthly contests held between November and March, not a single test. Each contest has just 5 problems, and students get 30 minutes to solve them, working individually and generally without a calculator. The problems are non-routine, meaning they reward creative reasoning over memorized formulas or speed. Scoring is simple: 1 point per correct answer, so a student can earn at most 25 points across the full season (5 contests times 5 points each). Individual scores are tracked contest by contest, and a team's overall score is the sum of its top 10 students' cumulative totals after all five contests. Because it spans five months, MOEMS also rewards consistency over one lucky day. Top individual scorers (based on percentile within their division) earn patches, pins, or trophies, but there's no pass/fail cutoff. It's designed to be encouraging at every score level.`,
    howToPrepare: `MOEMS problems are less about advanced topics and more about flexible thinking, since a typical problem might involve logic, patterns, number sense, basic combinatorics, or simple geometry, dressed up in a way that resists a plug-and-chug approach. The best preparation is regular, low-pressure exposure to this style of problem well before the season starts in November. Since the contest rewards reasoning speed under a 30-minute, 5-problem format, practicing with past MOEMS problem sets (available through the official program) is the most direct preparation. Encourage students to talk through their thinking rather than just checking the final answer, since MOEMS problems often have a pattern that becomes obvious once you see it. Because the season runs five months, steady, once-a-week practice from fall through winter tends to work better than a short cram right before a single contest. Reviewing mistakes contest to contest matters more than any one high score.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Can my child register for MOEMS individually?", a: "No. MOEMS only accepts registrations from schools or homeschool associations, submitted by a designated team coordinator (PICO). Ask your child's school if they already participate, or if a homeschool group nearby runs a team."},
      {q: "How much does it cost to participate?", a: "Registration is per team, not per student, and pricing depends on when the team registers, with early registration priced lower than late registration. Exact current-year fees are set by MOEMS each season, so check with your team's PICO or the official MOEMS site for the latest pricing."},
      {q: "How many students can be on a team?", a: "A single team can include up to 35 students, all competing under one school or homeschool association."},
      {q: "Is there a penalty for wrong answers?", a: "No. Students only gain points for correct answers, there's no deduction for an incorrect or blank response, so there's no downside to attempting every problem."},
      {q: "Which division should my child compete in?", a: "Division E covers grades 3 to 6 and Division M covers grades 6 to 8. If a team has any 7th or 8th grader, the whole team must compete in Division M, even if some members are younger."},
      {q: "Do MOEMS results matter for school admissions?", a: "No. MOEMS is a recognition and enrichment competition, not an admissions or placement test. It doesn't feed into school entrance decisions the way SSAT or similar tests do."},
    ],
  },
  'amc-8': {
    whatIs: `The AMC 8 is a math competition for students in grade 8 and below (with a maximum age limit of under 15.5 years on competition day), run by the Mathematical Association of America (MAA), the same organization behind the well-known AMC 10 and AMC 12 competitions for older students. It's typically many students' first serious encounter with competition mathematics. Students don't register individually. Instead, they take the AMC 8 through their school, learning center, or a local test site that has registered as an official test center with the MAA. Students take part for recognition and enrichment rather than admissions: strong performers earn Honor Roll or Distinguished Honor Roll status, and the AMC 8 also serves as an on-ramp to the AMC 10 in later years, which is how students eventually work toward AIME and, ultimately, USAMO qualification. The AMC 8 alone doesn't qualify a student for AIME, only AMC 10/12 scores do.`,
    formatScoring: `The AMC 8 is a 25-question, multiple-choice competition with a 40-minute time limit, held annually during a designated week in January. Depending on the school or test center, it can be taken on paper or digitally, since the MAA now supports both formats. Scoring is straightforward: 1 point for each correct answer, 0 points for a wrong or blank answer, with no penalty for guessing, so there's no reason to leave a question unanswered if time allows. The maximum possible score is 25. Top performers are recognized with Honor Roll (roughly the top 5% of that year's test-takers) and Distinguished Honor Roll, sometimes shortened to DHR (roughly the top 1%), though the exact score cutoff for each shifts slightly year to year depending on how the whole pool performs. Students may only take the AMC 8 once per year.`,
    howToPrepare: `The AMC 8 covers middle-school-level math, but the questions are designed to test reasoning under time pressure rather than raw content knowledge. Core topic areas include counting and probability, estimation, proportional reasoning, elementary geometry (including the Pythagorean theorem), spatial visualization, interpreting graphs and tables, and some early algebra such as linear and quadratic patterns showing up in the later, harder questions. Because it's timed at under 2 minutes per question on average, the biggest preparation win is practicing with past official AMC 8 papers (widely available and free) under real time constraints, not just working problems untimed. Students who are already comfortable with school math but haven't seen competition-style problems typically benefit from a few months of targeted practice, working through past papers, reviewing wrong answers carefully, and learning common problem-solving techniques (like working backward from answer choices, or looking for patterns instead of brute-forcing algebra). A steady one-to-two-month runway before the January test date, rather than a last-minute cram, tends to work best.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "How do I register my child for the AMC 8?", a: "You can't register directly with the MAA. A school, learning center, or approved test center registers as the host and enrolls students; ask your child's school if they participate, or look for a local math club or test center that offers it."},
      {q: "What does it cost?", a: "Registration fees are paid by the hosting school or center to the MAA (with different rates for early, regular, and late registration), and the school or center may then pass along a per-student fee. Exact current pricing is set by the MAA each season, so check with the host institution."},
      {q: "Can my child retake the AMC 8 if they don't do well?", a: "No, the AMC 8 is offered once per year during a single designated week in January, and students may only take it once in that window."},
      {q: "Does a good AMC 8 score help with AIME or college admissions?", a: "Not directly. AMC 8 doesn't lead to AIME qualification (only AMC 10/12 scores do). It's primarily a recognition and skill-building competition, though some families do mention strong results as an extracurricular highlight."},
      {q: "What's a good score on the AMC 8?", a: "There's no fixed good score, since cutoffs move year to year based on how the whole pool performs, but Honor Roll (around the top 5%) and Distinguished Honor Roll (around the top 1%) are the recognized benchmarks to aim for."},
      {q: "Is the AMC 8 the same as the AMC 10?", a: "No. AMC 8 is for grade 8 and below and covers middle-school content. AMC 10 is for grades 10 and below and covers more advanced material, including topics that can lead to AIME qualification."},
    ],
  },
  kangaroo: {
    whatIs: `Math Kangaroo is an international math competition open to students from kindergarten through grade 12, with the U.S. edition run by the nonprofit Math Kangaroo USA, NFP (the questions themselves are created by the International Mathematical Kangaroo Committee based in France). It's one of the most widely taken math competitions in the world, and in the U.S. it's a popular first competition for elementary and middle school students because it's welcoming to a wide range of skill levels. Students register individually (not through a school team) via an approved local test center or online option, and take part purely for enrichment and recognition. There's no admissions or placement use; it's designed to make competition math approachable and fun, with a scoring system that rewards attempting every question rather than punishing wrong guesses.`,
    formatScoring: `Math Kangaroo groups students into levels by grade, and each level takes the same 75-minute multiple-choice test as one adjacent grade (for example, grades 1 and 2 share a test, grades 3 and 4 share another). Students in grades 1 to 4 answer 24 questions, and students in grades 5 through 12 answer 30 questions, each with 5 answer choices. Questions are grouped into three difficulty tiers of equal size: the easiest third is worth 3 points each, the middle third 4 points each, and the hardest third 5 points each. There is no penalty for a wrong or blank answer, so a student's score is simply the sum of points earned from correct answers, with a maximum of 96 points for grades 1 to 4 and 120 points for grades 5 to 12. Results are reported with national and state rankings, and top scorers (roughly the top 20 nationally and top 3 per state per grade) receive special recognition.`,
    howToPrepare: `Math Kangaroo questions lean on visual and logical reasoning as much as calculation: expect problems involving patterns, spatial reasoning, basic logic, and creative applications of arithmetic or early geometry, often illustrated with pictures or diagrams rather than plain text. Because there's no penalty for wrong answers, part of the strategy is simply practicing enough that a student is comfortable making an educated guess rather than skipping a hard question. Since the test is timed at roughly 2 to 3 minutes per question on average, working through official past-year Math Kangaroo papers (available on the Math Kangaroo USA site) under timed conditions is the most useful prep, more so than generic math worksheets. The event runs once a year in March, so a couple of months of light, regular practice from January onward, focused on past papers rather than new content, is usually enough for younger students, since the goal is more about building comfort with the question style than mastering new math.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "How do I register my child?", a: "Registration is done individually online through the Math Kangaroo USA website, choosing an approved local test center (schools, learning centers, or community organizations) near you, rather than through your child's school directly (though some schools do host their own center)."},
      {q: "How much does it cost?", a: "Regular registration (mid-September through the end of December) is priced lower than late registration (January through early February), with a defined fee for each window. Check the official site for the exact current-year amounts."},
      {q: "When is the competition held?", a: "Math Kangaroo takes place once a year, on the third Thursday in March, at the same time across all participating centers."},
      {q: "Can my child retake it if they miss the date or want to improve their score?", a: "No, it's offered once per year on a single fixed date. If a student misses it, the next opportunity is the following year."},
      {q: "Is there a penalty for guessing?", a: "No. There's no deduction for a wrong or blank answer, so students are encouraged to attempt every question."},
      {q: "Do Math Kangaroo results affect school admissions?", a: "No. It's an enrichment and recognition competition with no bearing on school admissions or placement."},
    ],
  },
  ssat: {
    whatIs: `The SSAT (Secondary School Admission Test) is a standardized admission test used by private and independent schools across the U.S. and Canada, administered by the Enrollment Management Association (EMA), a nonprofit organization. Unlike MOEMS or Math Kangaroo, the SSAT is a genuine admissions test: schools use scores, alongside grades, essays, and interviews, to evaluate applicants and, in some cases, to help place incoming students into appropriately leveled classes. There are three levels based on the grade a student is currently in: Elementary Level for grades 3 and 4, Middle Level for grades 5 through 7, and Upper Level for grades 8 through 11. Students typically take the level matching their current grade when applying to the next school year. Because it's used specifically for private/independent school admissions (not public school placement), it matters most for families applying to independent day or boarding schools.`,
    formatScoring: `The Elementary Level SSAT has 5 sections (Quantitative, Verbal, Reading, a picture-prompt Writing Sample, and an unscored Experimental section) and runs about 2 hours 5 minutes including one break. The Middle and Upper Levels have 6 sections (a Writing Sample, two Quantitative sections, Reading, Verbal, and an unscored Experimental section) and run about 3 hours 5 to 10 minutes including two breaks, depending on paper or computer format. Scoring differs by level. On the Elementary Level, students earn 1 point per correct answer with no penalty for wrong answers. On the Middle and Upper Levels, students earn 1 point per correct answer, lose a quarter point per incorrect answer, and lose nothing for a skipped question, so random guessing carries some risk on the harder levels. Scaled scores range from 900 to 1800 for Elementary, 1320 to 2130 for Middle, and 1500 to 2400 for Upper Level. Rather than a simple percentage, results are also reported as a percentile compared to other first-time test-takers over the past three years, which is the number admissions offices tend to focus on most.`,
    howToPrepare: `The SSAT's Quantitative (math) sections test arithmetic, pre-algebra, basic algebra (linear and quadratic patterns, slopes and intercepts), and geometry (area, perimeter, volume, coordinate geometry, properties of triangles and circles), generally at or slightly above the test-taker's current grade level. Reading and Verbal sections test vocabulary and comprehension, and the Writing Sample is unscored but sent to schools as a writing sample. Because the Quantitative sections are timed at 30 minutes for 25 questions each (about 72 seconds per question) with a wrong-answer penalty on Middle and Upper Levels, students benefit from practicing under real timed conditions and learning to skip rather than guess wildly on questions they're unsure of. Most families start preparing 1 to 3 months before the test date, working through official SSAT practice materials (the Official Guide or Official Practice Online), reviewing every incorrect answer, and building comfort with showing work on paper instead of trying to do calculations in their head, since the format rewards careful, methodical solving over speed alone.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "How much does the SSAT cost?", a: "Fees vary by level and testing format (standard paper, Prometric center, SSAT at Home, or international), and change from year to year, generally landing somewhere in the low-to-mid hundreds of dollars for Middle/Upper Level, with Elementary Level typically less. Check the official SSAT site for exact current pricing before registering."},
      {q: "Can my child retake the SSAT?", a: "Yes. Students can take the Standard SSAT multiple times within a testing year (roughly August through July), up to a set maximum number of attempts that varies by format, and can choose which score(s) to send to each school."},
      {q: "Do schools see every attempt, or can we choose which score to send?", a: "Families choose which score report(s) to send to each school, so an off day on one attempt doesn't have to be shared if a later attempt goes better."},
      {q: "What's considered a good SSAT score?", a: "There's no universal good score, since it's reported as a percentile against other first-time test-takers (often from selective independent schools), so what counts as competitive depends on the specific schools a student is applying to. It's worth checking the typical accepted-student range for each target school."},
      {q: "Is the SSAT the same everywhere, or does it depend on the school?", a: "The test itself is standardized, but each school sets its own bar for what score it considers competitive, and some schools weigh SSAT scores more heavily than others in admissions."},
      {q: "How is the SSAT different from other admission tests like the ISEE?", a: "Both are standardized admission tests for private/independent schools, but they're run by different organizations (SSAT by EMA, ISEE by ERB) with different formats and scoring scales; which one a family needs depends entirely on which test the target schools accept."},
    ],
  },
  map: {
    whatIs: `MAP Growth is a computer-adaptive assessment published by NWEA, used to measure achievement and growth in math, reading, language usage, and science for students in kindergarten through grade 12. Unlike a state exam, MAP isn't mandated nationwide, it's adopted at the discretion of individual schools and districts as an internal tool. Most schools that use it test students two to three times a year (commonly fall, winter, and spring) to track how much a student has grown since the last test and to compare performance to national norms. Teachers use MAP results to place students in the right instructional level, spot learning gaps early, group students for support or enrichment, and, in some districts, as one factor when screening for gifted and talented programs. It is not a pass/fail exam and has no bearing on grade promotion or graduation.`,
    formatScoring: `MAP Growth is computer-adaptive: if a student answers correctly, the next question gets slightly harder, and if they answer incorrectly, the next one gets slightly easier. This means no two students see exactly the same set of questions, and the test continually recalibrates to find each student's actual skill level rather than testing everyone against a fixed grade-level bar. The test is untimed, though most students finish a single subject in under an hour. Results are reported as a RIT (Rasch Unit) score, an equal-interval scale where a given point difference means roughly the same thing at any level, which is what makes it possible to track growth over months and years on one continuous scale. Scores are also translated into a percentile rank comparing a student to peers nationally who tested at the same time of year; the 50th percentile represents typical performance.`,
    howToPrepare: `Because MAP is adaptive and growth-focused rather than tied to a specific unit of content, NWEA itself advises against last-minute cramming, there's no fixed syllabus to memorize the night before. What genuinely helps is steady, grade-appropriate practice across the domains actually tested: number sense and problem-solving in math, reading comprehension and vocabulary, and language conventions, built up over the term rather than crammed. It also helps for a student to be comfortable navigating an on-screen test interface (scrolling, on-screen tools like a calculator or ruler at higher grades, flagging and returning to questions). Since the test recalibrates in real time, staying calm and simply attempting every question (rather than guessing randomly or rushing) leads to a more accurate score.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Is MAP a required state test?", a: "No. It's an optional tool that individual schools and districts choose to use; it is not a state or federal accountability exam like STAAR or NJSLA."},
      {q: "How often is MAP given?", a: "Typically two to three times per school year, at the start, middle, and/or end of the year, depending on the school's schedule."},
      {q: "What is a good RIT score?", a: "There's no universal good score; RIT scores are meant to be compared against a student's own past scores (growth) and against national grade-level norms (percentile), not judged in isolation."},
      {q: "Can a student fail MAP?", a: "No, there is no passing or failing threshold. It's a diagnostic and growth-tracking tool, not a certification test."},
      {q: "Is MAP used for gifted program placement?", a: "Sometimes. Some districts use a high MAP percentile (often around the 95th) as one data point among several when screening for gifted programs, but this varies by district and is never the sole criterion."},
      {q: "Can we retake MAP if a score seems off?", a: "There's no formal retake process, but because it's given multiple times a year as a matter of course, the next scheduled administration naturally provides an updated score."},
    ],
  },
  staar: {
    whatIs: `STAAR is Texas's statewide standardized testing program, administered by the Texas Education Agency (TEA). It measures how well a student has learned and can apply the Texas Essential Knowledge and Skills (TEKS), the state's academic standards. STAAR is given each spring in math and reading to students in grades 3 through 8, with science added in grades 5 and 8, and social studies in grade 8. At the high school level, STAAR shifts to End-of-Course (EOC) exams tied to specific classes: English I, English II, Algebra I, Biology, and U.S. History. STAAR results feed into Texas's school and district accountability ratings (the state's A-F system), and they carry real stakes for students too: 5th and 8th graders must pass the math and reading STAAR tests to be promoted to the next grade, and high schoolers generally must pass all five EOC exams to graduate.`,
    formatScoring: `Since a 2023 redesign, STAAR is administered primarily online and now limits multiple-choice questions to no more than 75% of any test. The rest of the test uses newer technology-enhanced item types: equation editor items (typing in a number, fraction, or expression), graphing items (plotting points or building a graph on screen), number line items, drag-and-drop, and hot text/multi-select items. STAAR is not strictly timed in minutes, but districts typically schedule three to four hours per test session, and any student needing more time may continue testing until the end of the school day, with seven hours as the absolute daily ceiling. Scores are converted to a scale score and sorted into four performance levels: Did Not Meet Grade Level, Approaches Grade Level, Meets Grade Level, and Masters Grade Level. Approaches Grade Level is the minimum passing bar.`,
    howToPrepare: `STAAR is built directly from the TEKS that Texas public schools teach year-round, so consistent classroom learning is the real foundation, not test-week cramming. Because of the 2023 redesign, students also need practice with the newer item formats: typing in equations or fractions, building graphs on screen, plotting on number lines, and dragging/dropping answers, since these require different skills than picking from four answer choices. TEA publishes real, retired STAAR questions (released test questions) that are the most reliable practice material available, since they reflect actual item difficulty and format. For 5th and 8th graders specifically, extra focus on math and reading is worthwhile given the grade-promotion stakes: a student who doesn't pass gets additional instruction and up to two more testing opportunities within the same school year before other promotion pathways are considered.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Who has to take STAAR?", a: "All Texas public school students in the tested grades and subjects (3-8 for math/reading, plus science and social studies at specific grades), and high schoolers enrolled in the five EOC courses. Students with significant cognitive disabilities may take an alternate assessment, STAAR Alternate 2, instead."},
      {q: "Does my child have to pass STAAR to move to the next grade?", a: "Generally yes for 5th and 8th grade math and reading, under Texas's Student Success Initiative. In other grades, STAAR results are one factor among several that a school considers for promotion, not an automatic pass/fail gate."},
      {q: "Can students retake STAAR?", a: "Yes. 5th and 8th graders who don't pass get up to two additional testing opportunities the same year, along with extra instruction in between. High school EOC exams can also be retaken in later administrations."},
      {q: "Do STAAR scores affect graduation?", a: "Yes, students generally must pass all five EOC exams to graduate, though alternate pathways (such as review by a Graduation Committee) exist for students who haven't passed after multiple attempts."},
      {q: "What counts as a good score?", a: "Meets Grade Level or Masters Grade Level indicate solid to strong mastery. Approaches Grade Level is the passing threshold but reflects only partial mastery of grade-level skills."},
      {q: "Is STAAR timed?", a: "Not with a hard minute cap for most students; sessions are generally scheduled for three to four hours, and students needing more time can continue until the school day ends."},
    ],
  },
  njsla: {
    whatIs: `NJSLA is New Jersey's statewide standardized assessment, administered by the New Jersey Department of Education (NJDOE). It measures how well students are progressing toward the New Jersey Student Learning Standards in English Language Arts and Mathematics for grades 3 through 8 (plus specific high school math courses like Algebra I and Geometry), and in Science for grades 5, 8, and 11. NJSLA's main purpose is accountability and progress monitoring: it lets the state and districts publicly report how students are doing against grade-level standards and identify where schools need to improve. For most students, NJSLA is not tied to grade promotion or graduation (a separate exam, the NJGPA, handles the graduation requirement); results mainly inform school-level accountability and can factor into a district's instructional planning or support decisions for individual students. As of spring 2026, NJSLA moved to a computer-adaptive format (NJSLA-Adaptive) after field testing in fall 2025, replacing the previous fixed-form version statewide.`,
    formatScoring: `NJSLA is computer-based (paper testing is available only as an accommodation) and, as of the 2026 adaptive rollout, adjusts question difficulty to the student in real time. It's given during a set spring testing window each year. Math is typically delivered in two sessions, with the assessment taking roughly 150 minutes total across both sessions, though exact timing can vary somewhat by grade. Historically, NJSLA math has used a mix of machine-scored items (multiple-choice and technology-enhanced formats like drag-and-drop or graphing) and some hand-scored, constructed-response items where a student shows written work; the exact balance of these item types under the new adaptive format was still being finalized as of this writing. Scores for grades 3-8 are reported as a scale score from 10 to 90, mapped to four performance levels: Not Meeting Expectations, Partially Meeting Expectations, Meeting Expectations, and Exceeding Expectations.`,
    howToPrepare: `NJSLA is built directly from the New Jersey Student Learning Standards taught in class, so the strongest preparation is simply solid, consistent classroom learning throughout the year rather than test-specific cramming. Because some math items ask students to show or explain their reasoning, practicing how to write out a clear solution, not just arrive at a final answer, is genuinely useful prep, not just for the test but as a math skill in general. With the shift to a computer-adaptive format, students also benefit from being comfortable typing numeric or fraction answers, using on-screen tools, and navigating a computer-based test interface, since these mechanics can trip up an otherwise well-prepared student. NJDOE publishes released sample questions and testing guides that are the most reliable practice materials, since they reflect the actual item types and difficulty level used on the real assessment.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Who has to take NJSLA?", a: "All New Jersey public school students in grades 3-8 (ELA and Math), plus science in grades 5, 8, and 11, and specific high school math courses. New Jersey does not have a formal legal opt-out process, though families can refuse the test without facing a funding penalty to the school."},
      {q: "Do NJSLA scores affect grade promotion or graduation?", a: "No, not directly. NJSLA itself isn't the graduation gate in New Jersey; a separate exam, the NJGPA, serves that role. NJSLA scores can still inform a school's decisions about extra support or instructional placement."},
      {q: "What are NJSLA scores mainly used for?", a: "State and district accountability, tracking how well students statewide are meeting the learning standards, and helping schools identify where students need more support."},
      {q: "Can a student retake NJSLA?", a: "No, it's administered once per subject per year in a defined spring window, it isn't a retake-able exam the way an EOC or a college admissions test is."},
      {q: "What counts as a good score?", a: "Meeting Expectations or Exceeding Expectations indicate the student is on track with grade-level standards; Partially Meeting or Not Meeting flag a need for additional support."},
      {q: "Is NJSLA new this year?", a: "Its content and standards alignment aren't new, but the computer-adaptive delivery format (NJSLA-Adaptive) is new as of spring 2026, following field testing in fall 2025."},
    ],
  },
  cogat: {
    whatIs: `CogAT is a cognitive ability (reasoning) test published by Riverside Insights, given to groups of students from kindergarten through grade 12 (ages roughly 5 to 18, across ten test levels). Unlike MAP, STAAR, or NJSLA, CogAT is not an achievement test, it doesn't measure what a student has learned in school. Instead, it estimates a student's ability to reason and solve unfamiliar problems using verbal, quantitative, and nonverbal (visual/spatial) content. Its most common use in U.S. schools is as a screening tool for gifted and talented program identification, since it can surface strong reasoning ability in students whose classroom grades or achievement scores don't necessarily reflect it. Some schools also use CogAT results alongside achievement data to inform broader instructional planning. It is administered at a district's or school's discretion, not required by any state or federal mandate.`,
    formatScoring: `CogAT is organized into three batteries, each covering a different type of reasoning: Verbal (analogies, sentence completion, classification), Quantitative (number analogies, number puzzles, number series), and Nonverbal (figure matrices, paper folding, figure classification). For the youngest test-takers (kindergarten through grade 2), all three batteries are picture-based and untimed. From grade 3 up, each battery is timed, with about 10 minutes per subtest, and the full test runs roughly 90 to 120 minutes depending on the level, with 118 to 176 total questions across the grade range. Some schools use a shorter Screening Form that includes only the analogy-type subtest from each battery. Results are reported as a Standard Age Score (SAS, with a mean of 100), a percentile rank comparing the student to same-age peers nationally, and a stanine (a 1-9 band), along with separate scores for each of the three batteries plus an overall composite.`,
    howToPrepare: `Because CogAT measures reasoning ability rather than curriculum content, traditional studying (memorizing facts or formulas) doesn't help and isn't the point. What genuinely helps is familiarity with the question formats and thinking patterns the test uses, since a child who has simply never seen a picture-analogy or figure-matrix question before can underperform purely from unfamiliarity, not lack of ability. Age-appropriate practice with pattern recognition, spatial puzzles (mental rotation, paper folding), number sequences, and verbal analogy or classification games builds the specific skills tested. Because CogAT is designed to measure a fairly stable underlying ability, broader, ongoing enrichment (puzzles, logic games, encouraging kids to explain their reasoning) has more lasting value than last-minute drilling, though brief format familiarization in the weeks before the test is reasonable to reduce anxiety and unfamiliarity as confounding factors.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Is CogAT a math test?", a: "No. Its Quantitative Battery uses numbers, but it's testing reasoning with numbers, not math curriculum knowledge or computation skill."},
      {q: "Who takes CogAT?", a: "It varies by district. Many schools give it to an entire grade level (commonly around 2nd or 3rd grade) as part of gifted-program screening; others test individual students on referral."},
      {q: "What is a good CogAT score?", a: "An SAS around 100 is average for a student's age group. Many gifted programs look for a composite score around the 95th to 97th percentile or higher, but exact cutoffs vary widely by district and program."},
      {q: "Can a student retake CogAT?", a: "Policies vary by district; many limit retesting to about once a year or require a waiting period, since the test is designed to measure a fairly stable ability rather than something expected to change quickly."},
      {q: "Does CogAT replace achievement tests like MAP or STAAR?", a: "No, it's meant to complement them. Achievement tests measure what a student has learned; CogAT measures reasoning ability. Many gifted programs use both together for a fuller picture."},
      {q: "Is CogAT the same as an IQ test?", a: "It's similar in spirit and design to a cognitive ability test, but it's built specifically for K-12 educational screening (particularly gifted identification), not as a clinical IQ assessment."},
    ],
  },
  iar: {
    whatIs: `The Illinois Assessment of Readiness (IAR) is the state's official achievement test for public school students in grades 3 through 8, given each spring in English language arts (reading and writing) and mathematics. It's administered by the Illinois State Board of Education (ISBE) and replaced the PARCC exam in 2019, though many of its question types are drawn from the same PARCC item bank. IAR measures how well students are performing against the Illinois Learning Standards, which incorporate the Common Core. Schools and districts use the results for state accountability reporting, and teachers use them, alongside classroom performance, to see whether a student is on track for grade-level expectations. It is not a pass or fail exam and does not, by itself, decide grade promotion.`,
    formatScoring: `IAR is a computer-based test (with paper accommodations available). The English language arts portion is split into two units and math into three, and students complete these across multiple sessions over several days within the spring testing window, typically March through April. Question types include multiple choice, multiple select, drag-and-drop, equation editors, and other technology-enhanced items designed to mirror how students work in class. Students get scale scores, Reading typically ranges from 10 to 90 and Writing from 10 to 60, plus a placement of Higher, Middle, or Lower within specific reading, writing, and math skill areas. Starting with the 2025-26 school year, ISBE has standardized performance-level naming across its state tests, so families should expect updated level labels compared to earlier years.`,
    howToPrepare: `Because IAR is built on the Illinois Learning Standards (which align to Common Core), the most effective prep is steady, grade-level work in reading comprehension, evidence-based writing, and math throughout the school year rather than last-minute cramming. Since scoring rewards close reading and multi-step math reasoning over guessing, practicing how to explain and show work matters more than memorizing facts. Because the test is computer-based, it's worth having students try official released practice items so drag-and-drop, equation-builder, and multi-select formats aren't a surprise on test day. The test also runs across multiple sessions and several days, so building focus and stamina for sustained testing is a genuinely useful, exam-specific skill, not generic advice.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Who has to take IAR?", a: "All Illinois public school students in grades 3-8 take IAR in ELA and math each spring. Students with significant cognitive disabilities may instead take the Illinois Alternate Assessment (IAA)."},
      {q: "Is IAR a pass/fail test?", a: "No. It reports performance levels and scale scores, not a pass or fail outcome, and is used alongside classroom grades and other evidence."},
      {q: "Can a student retake IAR?", a: "No, IAR is given once a year in the spring; there is no official retake for the same school year."},
      {q: "How are IAR results used?", a: "Results feed into Illinois's school and district accountability report cards and help identify students who may need extra academic support."},
      {q: "When is IAR administered?", a: "During a spring testing window, typically March to April, with exact dates set locally within ISBE's window."},
      {q: "Is IAR the same as PARCC?", a: "No. IAR replaced PARCC in Illinois in 2019, though it reuses some PARCC-style item designs."},
    ],
  },
  aasa: {
    whatIs: `Arizona's Academic Standards Assessment (AASA) is Arizona's statewide achievement test, administered by the Arizona Department of Education to all public school students in grades 3 through 8, in English language arts (reading and writing) and mathematics. It replaced the earlier AzMERIT and AzM2 tests starting in the 2022-23 school year, with updated alignment to Arizona's academic standards. Third graders also complete an Oral Reading Fluency check as part of the ELA portion. Like other state assessments, AASA isn't something students study for the way they would for a class exam; it's given each spring to measure how well students are mastering Arizona's own grade-level standards, and results feed into school and district accountability and help identify students who need additional support.`,
    formatScoring: `AASA is administered by computer as the default mode and includes a mix of traditional multiple choice and multi-select questions along with technology-enhanced item types such as drag-and-drop, equation building, inline choice, hot text, and fill-in responses. It is given once a year in the spring across multiple testing sessions in both ELA and math. Students receive a scale score that places them into one of four performance levels: Level 1 (Minimally Proficient), Level 2 (Partially Proficient), Level 3 (Proficient), and Level 4 (Highly Proficient). The specific score ranges for each level vary by grade and subject. Scoring at Level 3 or 4 generally indicates a student is on track for the next grade level, while Level 1 or 2 signals a need for additional academic support.`,
    howToPrepare: `Since AASA is aligned specifically to Arizona's own academic standards rather than a generic curriculum, the strongest preparation is consistent, grade-level classroom work in reading, writing, and math throughout the year. Because the test is computer-based and timed, students benefit from taking official sample or practice tests on the same type of device they'll use on test day, so unfamiliar tools like drag-and-drop and equation builders don't slow them down. Since it's timed, practicing steady pacing under time pressure is a genuinely useful skill here, not just generic test advice. Preparation is best spread over the weeks and months leading up to the spring testing window rather than crammed at the last minute.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Who has to take AASA?", a: "All Arizona public school students in grades 3-8 take AASA in ELA and math each spring."},
      {q: "Is AASA the same as AzMERIT?", a: "AASA replaced AzMERIT (which had already become AzM2) starting in 2022-23. It covers the same grades and subjects but reflects updated standards alignment and reporting."},
      {q: "What happens if my child scores Level 1 or 2?", a: "It signals the student may need extra support to be ready for the next grade, but it's used together with other evidence, not as an automatic decision on its own."},
      {q: "Can a student retake AASA?", a: "No, it's given once a year in the spring, with no standard retake within the same school year."},
      {q: "How are AASA results used?", a: "For state and district accountability reporting, and to help schools identify students who need additional academic support."},
      {q: "When is AASA given?", a: "Each spring; exact dates are set by the Arizona Department of Education within the statewide testing window."},
    ],
  },
  gmas: {
    whatIs: `The Georgia Milestones Assessment System (GMAS) is Georgia's statewide assessment program, administered by the Georgia Department of Education, spanning grades 3 through high school. In grades 3-8, students take end-of-grade (EOG) assessments in English language arts and math (with science and social studies at certain grades). In high school, students take end-of-course (EOC) assessments tied to specific courses such as Algebra I, US History, Biology, and ninth-grade literature. GMAS measures how well students have mastered Georgia's own content standards, and results are used for state and district accountability, and, for the high school EOC, count directly toward a student's final course grade.`,
    formatScoring: `GMAS uses a mix of selected-response and open-ended, constructed-response items in ELA and math, plus a writing component that appears at every grade level and course. It also includes some norm-referenced items so results can be compared nationally. The state has been transitioning testing to online administration as the primary mode, with paper and pencil available as backup. For high school EOC tests, the score contributes 20% to the student's final grade in that course. Performance is reported using four achievement levels: Beginning Learners, Developing Learners, Proficient Learners, and Distinguished Learners, with the latter two levels considered indicators of being on track for college and career readiness.`,
    howToPrepare: `GMAS is built directly on the Georgia Standards of Excellence, so the most effective prep is steady engagement with classroom curriculum throughout the year rather than a short review before test day. Because a writing task and open-ended, constructed-response items appear at every grade and course, practicing how to construct evidence-based written answers is genuinely important here, not just answering multiple choice questions. For high school EOC exams, since the score is 20% of the final course grade, ongoing coursework performance is itself the most direct form of preparation, with focused review closer to the testing window. Students who don't meet the standard on an EOC also get a further retest opportunity, so a first attempt is not the only chance.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Who has to take GMAS?", a: "All Georgia public school students in grades 3-8 take the relevant EOG components, and high schoolers take the EOC test tied to each designated course they're enrolled in."},
      {q: "Does GMAS affect my child's grade?", a: "For high school EOC courses, yes, it counts as 20% of the final course grade. For grades 3-8 EOG, it doesn't factor into report card grades directly, but Georgia law uses certain grade-level results (such as third-grade reading, and fifth and eighth grade reading/math) as one factor in grade promotion decisions."},
      {q: "Can a student retest?", a: "Yes, for high school EOC, students who score below the required grade-conversion threshold may retest during the next available testing window, including a summer option if the original test was in spring. There is no standard retake for grades 3-8 EOG within the same year."},
      {q: "How are EOG results used?", a: "For state and district accountability, and as one input (not the only one) into certain grade promotion decisions required under Georgia law."},
      {q: "When is GMAS given?", a: "EOG assessments are given in spring; EOC assessments are given at the end of each semester or course, with additional mid-month retest windows built into the calendar."},
    ],
  },
  sba: {
    whatIs: `The Smarter Balanced Assessment (SBA), also known as SBAC, is a state achievement test in English language arts/literacy and math used by a consortium of member states rather than any single state. Historically this has included states such as California, Washington, Oregon, Nevada, Hawaii, and Connecticut, though exact membership has shifted over time, so families should confirm current participation with their own state's education department. It's given to students in grades 3-8 and one grade in high school. Like other state tests, it exists for state and district accountability and to give a common, standards-based picture of whether students are on track, and it's built and maintained collaboratively across member states rather than by a single state agency.`,
    formatScoring: `SBA is a computer adaptive test, meaning the difficulty of later questions adjusts based on how a student answers earlier ones, so two students can see different sets of questions depending on their performance. It also includes a performance task portion requiring longer, multi-step written or applied responses. Unlike many state tests, SBA is generally untimed, students are given as much time as they need within the school day or testing window. Results are reported as a scale score on a continuous range (roughly 2000 to 3000, increasing across grade levels) mapped to four achievement levels. Member states sometimes use different level names (for example, novice, developing, proficient, advanced), but Levels 3 and 4 generally indicate a student is on track for college and career readiness.`,
    howToPrepare: `Because SBA is adaptive, harder questions appear specifically because a student is doing well, so genuine command of grade-level reading, writing, and math standards matters more here than test-taking tricks or guessing strategies. Since the test includes performance tasks requiring extended written responses (connecting a reading passage to a writing prompt, or working through a multi-step math problem with justification), practicing that kind of extended, evidence-based response is more useful prep than multiple choice drilling alone. Students also benefit from trying official state-published practice tests to get comfortable with on-screen tools like the highlighter, calculator, and digital notepad. Because it's untimed, the emphasis in prep should be on sustained focus and thoroughness rather than speed.`,
    faqs: [
      {q: "Which states use SBA?", a: "It's used by states that are members of the Smarter Balanced Assessment Consortium; membership has changed over the years, so check your own state department of education's site to confirm current participation."},
      {q: "Who has to take it?", a: "General education students in grades 3-8 and one high school grade in participating states; an alternate assessment is available for students with significant cognitive disabilities."},
      {q: "Is SBA timed?", a: "No, there is no official overall time limit; students are given as much time as they need within the school day or testing window."},
      {q: "Can a student retake SBA?", a: "No, it's a once-a-year summative assessment with no standard retake in the same year."},
      {q: "Can my child opt out?", a: "Some member states allow parents to opt a student out of state testing, including SBA, but this varies by state, so check your local district or state education department's policy directly rather than assuming."},
      {q: "How are SBA results used?", a: "For state and district accountability reporting, and to indicate whether a student is on track toward grade-level and college/career readiness benchmarks."},
    ],
  },
};
